        "type": "thinking",
        "thinking": "Now I have a better picture. This is the Cachet status page application. The core application logic is in the `cachethq/core` package which isn't installed yet. \n\nLooking at the project:\n- It's a status page system with components, incidents, etc.\n- It uses Filament for the admin panel\n- There's a public status page\n- Users authenticate to manage the status page\n- The core models/controllers are in the `cachethq/core` package\n\nSince the vendor directory doesn't exist, I can't look at the core code. However, based on my knowledge of Cachet, the key business events would be around:\n- User authentication\n- Component status changes\n- Incident creation and updates\n- Subscriber management\n\nMost of the application logic lives in the `cachethq/core` package, but I can still instrument the local project by creating a PostHogService, setting up the configuration, and hooking into the AppServiceProvider and User model where I have access to the code.\n\nLooking at the routes, they're mostly empty since the core package handles the actual routing. I'll plan events that make sense for a status page and can be implemented in the files available to me locally. I'll create a dedicated PostHog service class and configuration file, then hook into Laravel's built-in authentication events through the AppServiceProvider to capture login, logout, and registration activities. For the events JSON file, I'll define a reasonable set of events that align with what a status page application would track.\n\nGenerating event definitions... Generating event definitions... I'm realizing that `status_page_viewed` makes sense as the top of a conversion funnel leading to notification subscriptions. But I need to be practical about implementation—since the core package isn't installed, I can only reliably track auth events through Laravel's built-in system. For model events tied to the core package's admin panel, I'd need to know the exact model class names, which I don't have access to. So I'll focus on what I can actually instrument with the available information. I'll create the PostHog events configuration file and then review the reference documentation to finalize the implementation plan.",
